	<h1>
SBRN Celebrates Five Years of Innovation
</h1>
	<div class="page-title-hline">&nbsp;</div>
	










<!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA - START -->



		<div class="floatright">
			<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="sidebar" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_sidebar --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_sidebar --> <!-- InstanceEndEditable -->

<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Sidebar" --><!-- InstanceEndEditable --><br class="hide" />
			</div>


			<div class="contentcolumn">
				<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="maincontent" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_maincontent --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_maincontent -->

	<div id="entry-202">
		<div class="entry-header">
			<!--<h2 class="asset-name entry-title">
SBRN Celebrates Five Years of Innovation
</h2>-->
			<div class="entry-meta" title="2010-08-27T17:46:22-05:00">Friday Aug 27, 2010</div>
		</div>
	
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<img alt="SBRN-3.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/SBRN-3.jpg" class="mt-image-left" style="float: left; margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt;" height="316" width="220" />The NSERC <a href="http://www.solarbuildings.ca/en/network">Solar Buildings Research Network</a> recently celebrated five years of groundbreaking research and cutting-edge activities with three days of special meetings at its Concordia University headquarters. These meetings culminated in a special daylong workshop that brought together SBRN researchers, industrial partners and potential new participants and collaborators to discuss research, development and demonstration initiatives. The day consisted of four panel discussions related to major research areas including net-zero energy housing, net-zero energy commercial buildings and communities and the building integration of solar energy systems. The workshop also enabled important discussions between industry, academia and government that are essential in the development of the next phase of the SBRN.<br /><br />The workshop was opened by keynote speaker, Concordia's Vice President of Research and Graduate Studies, <b>Louise Dandurand</b>. In her welcoming speech, Dandurand noted that she was pleased and proud that Concordia "has had the privilege of hosting the NSERC Solar Buildings Research Network" because it so amply exemplifies the University's research mission. She was followed by <b>Terry Hollands</b>, Chairman of the Board (SBRN) and Distinguished Professor Emeritus at the Department of Mechanical Engineering of the <a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.uwaterloo.ca/" title="University of Waterloo" rel="homepage">University of Waterloo</a>. Representing the Board, Hollands read out a glowing "report card" on the network, its members, and its output. "The Board feels that the network has set a golden example," said Hollands, who noted that serving as Chairman "has been a really rewarding experience."<br /><br /><img alt="SBRN-4.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/SBRN-4.jpg" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0pt auto 20px;" height="330" width="440" />The first round of panels then began, focusing on net-zero energy housing. Co-chaired by Josef Ayoub (NRCan) and R√©mi Charron (CMHC), the panel featured presentations by Bradley Berneche (Maisons Alouette), Michel Bernier (√0cole Polytechnique), Steven Crowell (Canadian Home Builders' Association) Alan Fung (<a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.ryerson.ca/" title="Ryerson University" rel="homepage">Ryerson University</a>), and Sevag Pogharian (SPD).&nbsp; Discussion was focused on lessons learned from the EQuilibrium Housing Demonstration Initiative, and methods of designing and building more cost-effective NZEHs in the future. Then it was on to the second panel, which focused on "smart solar buildings" and was led by <b>Andreas Athienitis </b>and <b>Paul Fazio</b> , long-time colleagues from Concordia's Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science. As the director of the SBRN, Athienitis suffered through friendly ribbing from the audience with a bright smile as he spoke of his research into solar energy before handing the floor over to Paul Fazio, who described the efforts of their graduate students into developing low-cost energy efficient housing for northern climes. The panel went on to include presentations by Wayne Chang (Pivotry Consulting), Michael Collins (University of Waterloo), Milfred Hammerbacher (Canadian Solar Inc.), Simon Langlois (Dupont), Yves Poissant (NRCan),&nbsp; Deo Prasad (<a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.unsw.edu.au/" title="University of New South Wales" rel="homepage">University of New South Wales</a>, Australia), and Carey Simonson (University of Saskatchewan). <br /><br /><img alt="SBRN-2.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/SBRN-2.jpg" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0pt auto 20px;" height="173" width="440" />The group then broke for lunch, with board members getting the chance to mingle (and endure a photoshoot) in the Dean's Conference Room, while the rest of the attendees gathered for a sunlit lunch in the EV atrium. The session then resumed with a panel on Net-zero energy commercial buildings and demand management, co-chaired by Jim Love from the <a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.ucalgary.ca/" title="University of Calgary" rel="homepage">University of Calgary</a>, and Ian Beausoleil-Morrison from <a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.carleton.ca/" title="Carleton University" rel="homepage">Carleton University</a>. Marc Dugr√© (R√©gulvar), Sophie Hosatte (NRCan), Howard Yaphe (CanLyte/Philips), Radu Zmeureanu (Concordia University), Guy Newsham (IRC-NRCC) then gave presentations focusing on special issues concerning the development of cost-effective net-zero energy commercial buildings, including peak loads, load management, thermal and/or electrical energy storage, advanced lighting/daylighting systems, and dynamic envelopes (e.g. smart facades with integrated control of shading and solar collection/conversion/storage).<br /><br /><div align="center"><img alt="SBRN-1.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/SBRN-1.jpg" class="mt-image-center" style="text-align: center; display: block; margin: 0pt auto 20px;" height="133" width="440" /><i>The Board of Directors of the SBRN</i><br /></div><div align="center"><br /></div>The workshop wrapped up with a panel on the concept of net-zero energy communities, co-chaired by Steve Harrison from <a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.queensu.ca/" title="Queen's University" rel="homepage">Queen's University</a>, and Karen Pero from NRCan. The panel included presentations by Liuchen Chang (<a href="http://www.unb.ca/">UNB</a>), Chris Kennedy (<a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.utoronto.ca/" title="University of Toronto" rel="homepage">University of Toronto</a>), Ted Kesik (University of Toronto), Doug McClenahan (<a href="http://www.nrcan-rncan.gc.ca/com/index-eng.php">NRCan</a>), and Bill Wong (SAIC) on how advancing from net-zero energy building-level design to net-zero energy at the community level introduces new opportunities and challenges. The session focused on topics such as seasonal thermal storage, centralized energy systems, and solar optimization at the community level. Lessons learned from the Drake Landing solar community and other sustainable communities were also discussed.<br /><br />The Network's director, Andreas Athienitis--professor in the Department of Building, Civil and Environmental Engineering within the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science--felt that the workshop was a great success. "We are now in the final year of the present SBRN research program," he explained. "The Network has considerable achievements to show in its work. Many of its graduates have taken up faculty positions in Canadian and US universities and are playing a key role in the development of new academic programs and research initiatives aimed at developing the technologically advanced sustainable buildings of the future." The future is undoubtedly bright for the NSERC Solar Buildings Research Network, as Athienitis and his colleagues work on new funding initiatives to continue the work of SBRN focused on smart net-zero energy buildings and communities. <br /><div></div><br /><div><br /></div>

			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
	
	
	
